{
  "texts": [
    "This study makes the following contributions: (1) We introduce a skill-oriented perspective on top management teams for the AI context (TMT AI literacy) and uncover its positive effects on AI orientation and HR-related AI implementation ability.",
    "Therefore, we depart from the prevalent role-oriented perspective in upper echelons' IS research (Ding et al., 2014; Li et al., 2021) and focus on the literacy of executive teams instead of the presence of individual roles.",
    "We extend the discourse by answering the known limitations of a role-oriented approach (Haffke et al., 2016).",
    "In addition, we go beyond existing AI literacy research by considering executives in addition to users and developers (Sambasivan et al., 2021; Wang et al., 2022).",
    "(2) We introduce HR-related AI implementation ability in the upper echelons context, bridging the gap between AI value identification, achieved through AI orientation (Li et al., 2021), and AI value realization, achieved through AI implementation (Weber et al., 2022)."
  ]
}